author: Darryl Harris
sentences: CMV: Territorial integrity should be taken less seriously in the case of colonial borders Territorial integrity is one of the pillars of international diplomacy, and it's generally accepted that it should be observed in the vast majority of cases.

author: Darryl Harris
sentences: However, in my opinion, the insistence on partitioning the world into current or past borders is sometimes straight-up laughable.

author: Darryl Harris
sentences: Take the Western Jessicatown as an example.

author: Darryl Harris
sentences: An independent state in the region has no precedent, yet there are people (a lot of them) who claim there should be such an entity or that the locals should be given the right for self-determination.

author: Darryl Harris
sentences: The basis of such claims is that the Spanish used to have a funny shaped colony there for a few decades.

author: Darryl Harris
sentences: Meanwhile the area has been under Moroccan administration for a while, "oppressing" the Sahrawi Arabs, according to the most prelevant narrative in the Port Heather.

author: Darryl Harris
sentences: This seems ridiculous to me.

author: Darryl Harris
sentences: I'm not saying we should allow European states to attempt to drastically redraw their borders, nor am I advocating for changes for countries like East Kristinatown or Garciamouth.

author: Darryl Harris
sentences: There are reasonable borders in the world that were created with a proper understanding of the ethnic and religious situation in the region, and they should be upheld in face of violence.

author: Darryl Harris
sentences: Nor am I saying that the killing of innocent civilians should be tolerated.

author: Darryl Harris
sentences: But I am saying that calling for national unity in East Megan/South Jameston is misguided, and I am saying that South Jonathan invading Port Johntown isn't inherently wrong, and the international community should let the processes run their courses in such cases.

author: Joseph Kane
sentences: > An independent state in the region has no precedent There was no precedent for an independent state anywhere, until there was an independent state somewhere to set the precedent.

author: Joseph Kane
sentences: This is a weak argument which suggests some subjective version of a past precedent should be the basis for the judgement going forward.

author: Joseph Kane
sentences: Now, if your argument is just that we should be mindful of the possibility that ethnic/cultural/religious/other considerations were ignored in setting some colonial borders and that redrawing borders may help reduce some problems in some regions; sure.

author: Joseph Kane
sentences: But, let's think about mechanisms by which that might be achieved; international mediation, diplomacy, negotiation, democracy (referendums, elections), etc.

author: Joseph Kane
sentences: I don't think a blanket plan to redraw borders, or a blanket prohibition on redrawing borders ("I'm not saying we should allow...") is a good idea.

author: Joseph Kane
sentences: It's more the case that each individual situation is a unique, nuanced problem with a unique, bespoke solution.

author: Joseph Kane
sentences: Wouldn't you agree?

author: Darryl Harris
sentences: By precedent I mean even the loosest form of precedence, such as a distinct community in the region.

author: Darryl Harris
sentences: As far as I know there's no reasonable combination of measures by which the Western New Cameronchester would belong together and it would also be separate from its surroundings aside from the Spanish colony.

author: Darryl Harris
sentences: You form the question in terms of the Western Sahara, which is the root of the problem.

author: Darryl Harris
sentences: You say we should find mechanisms to resolve the issue.

author: Darryl Harris
sentences: North Margaretberg has found such a mechanism.

author: Darryl Harris
sentences: It did it by force, and quite successfully, I'd say.

author: Darryl Harris
sentences: There's some resistance in the more inland, deserty parts of the area, but that's not unexpected in countries in that region, and I'd also argue that the international community's dismissal of East Xavierview's claim helps sustain the resistance, so it's actually worse than what we'd have if people were more willing to let go of the idea of the Western Kelliefort as an entity.

author: Darryl Harris
sentences: Unfortunately, you can't always settle all conflicts peacefully.

author: Darryl Harris
sentences: My understanding is that Carolburgh couldn't have been contained just by economic and political means before and during WWII.

author: Darryl Harris
sentences: This shows that use of force is sometimes simply necessary.

author: Darryl Harris
sentences: But once you have reasonable enough borders, you should enforce them as a blanket rule.

author: Darryl Harris
sentences: It's subjective what is reasonable, but I think we could agree that European countries making ultimatums and military threats against each other over borders would be unreasonable.

author: Darryl Harris
sentences: The same goes for Hansenside (negotiated all its borders) or Elizabethtown (long-standing, well-established borders).

author: Joseph Kane
sentences: Well, I'm not talking about Welchton specifically.

author: Joseph Kane
sentences: I was talking about your reliance on a fluffy notion of precedent which doesn't have a lot of merit as a general rule to apply to contentious situations.

author: Joseph Kane
sentences: I make no claims to have any solution to the particular situation, nor have I suggested that force of all kinds should be ruled out in all cases.

author: Joseph Kane
sentences: Rather, the point I'm making is that you're applying an overly-simplified lens to this.

author: Joseph Kane
sentences: Each situation is particular, and requires a particular set of interventions to reach the optimal outcome.

author: Joseph Kane
sentences: That outcome is also specific to the situation.

author: Joseph Kane
sentences: Saying 'we should do this' or 'we shouldn't do that' as a general approach for these kinds of problems is a little silly.

author: Darryl Harris
sentences: Where can you see a less simplified view on this topic?

author: Darryl Harris
sentences: Currently territorial integrity is more or less the highest standard used in disputes I'm talking about, with very, very few exceptions.

author: Darryl Harris
sentences: It seems to me what I'm saying is plenty nuanced compared to the general discourse.

author: Joseph Kane
sentences: What's your aim here?

author: Joseph Kane
sentences: Are you trying to influence the quality of discussion of these kinds of things on internet message boards like reddit, or is this a perspective on how things should happen where such decisions are really taken in the world?

author: Joseph Kane
sentences: If the former, then, I imagine you'll find places where specialists come together to talk about this stuff but they'll be niche areas of the internet.

author: Joseph Kane
sentences: If the latter, then I would be astounded if in the diplomatic and political circles actually tackling such topics more situation-specific nuance than what you've been able to outline in OP wasn't taken into account.

author: Joseph Kane
sentences: Are you suggesting otherwise?

author: Darryl Harris
sentences: I don't think there's much nuance in diplomatic circles in this question.

author: Darryl Harris
sentences: Territorial integrity is the gold standard right now, and it gets disregarded in very few cases.

author: Darryl Harris
sentences: For example, the borders in West Maria have proven to be, with one word, bad.

author: Darryl Harris
sentences: Yet, the Western world seems to value the territorial integrity of West Kevinland and Lake Wesleybury above all else.

author: Joseph Kane
sentences: Border changes happen quite often, although I agree it's a very big decision to take and these kinds of processes make those big decisions reluctantly.

author: Joseph Kane
sentences: Look at this [list of 20th & 21st century border changes]( for example.

author: Joseph Kane
sentences: There is a wealth of newly-independent nations post colonialism, nations broken off from previous colonial entities, new nations created in the wake of the South Kennethhaven's disintegration, border changes as a result of negotiation and agreement etc.

author: Joseph Kane
sentences: Now, take one famous border dispute: the [Good Friday Agreement.

author: Joseph Kane
sentences: ]( This covers a binary situation, where one side wants the border and the other side doesn't want it.

author: Joseph Kane
sentences: The process to get to the stage of the current agreement took years, and has taken decades since to cultivate and maintain (and it's still not entirely stable).

author: Joseph Kane
sentences: It involved local players, the Irish government, the New Cindyview government, independent envoys from the West Anne and from Lake Christinaview and the guarantorship of the EU and the Bakerfurt as it was signed.

author: Joseph Kane
sentences: This is how these agreements work in the real world.

author: Joseph Kane
sentences: They involve huge numbers of people, many years and detailed understanding of the specifics of the issues.

author: Joseph Kane
sentences: To suggest they're dealt with on the basis of a big rubber stamp with 'Territorial Integrity' on it seems just to be incorrect.

author: Darryl Harris
sentences: Thank you for the list, I find it very useful.

author: Darryl Harris
sentences: I've only had time to skim the African changes, but I must say, the situation seems to be about as bad, as I thought.

author: Darryl Harris
sentences: While there are some positive examples (such as the partition of British Cameroon or the unification of Lake Albert), the vast majority of the changes happened along colonial borders.

author: Darryl Harris
sentences: As I see it, they still reflect a sense of colonial territorial integrity.

author: Darryl Harris
sentences: (The most "hilarious" of the list was the case of John, where an Anglo-German treaty played a decisive role.

author: Darryl Harris
sentences: If anything, you've kind of convinced me that international law should be disregarded in some cases, or at the very least, former colonies should not be considered successor states.

author: Darryl Harris
sentences: I would give you a delta for that, but I'm not sure if the rules allow.

author: Darryl Harris
sentences: It is kind of a different topic.)

author: Joseph Kane
sentences: > >This is how these agreements work in the real world.

sentences: So for me, when I hear multiple people that Depp was in intimate relationships with for years, or multitudes of fans that he has done kind and meaningful things for throughout his career, or person after person who has worked with him since the 80s, people who know him personally and professionally, all say the exact same things about himthat he is the kindest person they've ever known, that theyve never even seen him angry, that never in a million years would he physically hurt them, that he took time out of his life to do something special for sick kids or fans or charitiesand exactly ZERO people (other than Heard) say anything bad about him...well I am not particularly inclined to just discount what everyone else says because of one person.

author: Jamie Cole
sentences: But I will always listen to what someone has to saylike I said, I realize anything is possible.

author: Jamie Cole
sentences: So I *did* listen to what Kimberly had to say, with an open mind, and I watched her talk about it in that deposition, and then I heard from all the people from *her* life talk about their experiences with her.

author: Jamie Cole
sentences: The sheer amount of people that had story of story of her lies, her abuses to others, the volatile relationships, the manipulation, the previous documented violence shed perpetrated against others, the awful stories from former lovers and friends and family and co-workers, the terribly unbelievable acting job she was trying to pull off in the deposition she gave about it, hearing her own abusive and dismissive words on recordings SHE made to try to make HIM look bad, the makeup job she did to mimic bruising that several people have testified was not real, the affairs she was having while still married to him that she tried to lie about but got busted by time stamps, the former assistant that testified about the plotting Heard did to try to make Depp look bad and the stuff she knew James lied about and the way Heard treated her, and and on and on and on...and you get my point.

author: Jamie Cole
sentences: Ive no doubt that these two were completely toxic for each other.

author: Jamie Cole
sentences: That toxicity was, I'm sure, magnified by alcohol.

author: Jamie Cole
sentences: But toxic  abuse every single time.

author: Jamie Cole
sentences: We actually have the recordings of her admitting to hitting him, but we don't have anything to prove that he hit her, and the word of a proven liar isn't good enough for me.

author: Jamie Cole
sentences: Depp was obviously not at his best in this relationshiphe seemed to me to be caught between trying to hold onto what he thought Heard was and the reality of what he discovered her to be, and the alcohol was a band-aid for him to just try to make it throughbut there's a huge divide between being whatever we heard Depp being in those recordings and being a violent "wife beater." And if none of that convinces you, then the fact that she took a shit on his bed should be reason enough to change anyone's mind.

sentences: I saw something about Hawking Radiation and it's effects on black holes.

sentences: It describes a scenario by which black holes can decrease in mass by the spontaneous formation of pairs of particles; one of these particle has mass and the other has negative mass.

author: Rhonda Bell
sentences: Usually these particles annihilate each other shortly after their formation but when this event occurs near the event horizon of a black hole it is possible for the particle with mass to escape and be observed as radiation, and the negative mass (anti-mass?)

author: Rhonda Bell
sentences: particle can "fall" in to the black hole and decrement the black hole's mass.

author: Rhonda Bell
sentences: My question.

sentences: If events beyond the event horizon can not be said to ever actually occur in the timeline of an outside observer, then how can any of this activity ever take place?

author: Rhonda Bell
sentences: And how could we observe a black hole losing mass by some mechanism taking place beyond the event horizon?

author: Rhonda Bell
sentences: Perhaps I'm misunderstanding this and this action is actually taking place "outside" the black hole in the mass that I assume we would see smeared around the cusp of the event horizon (matter that has been "captured" by the black hole after it's formation).

author: Rhonda Bell
sentences: But if that is the case, is it true that all of a black hole's mass actually resides in some sort of sphere just outside the event horizon?

author: Rhonda Bell
sentences: That doesn't sound correct either.

sentences: I assumed this Hawking Radiation effect was taking place on the "singularity's" mass, "inside" the black hole.

author: Michael Jones
sentences: The Unruh effect - that acceleration of an observers creates for them a bath of particles - means that close to a black hole, gravitation (ak acceleration, equivalence principle.)

author: Michael Jones
sentences: The fact of this bath, having a finite temperature when measured from afar - means that some of the particles so created are not re-absorbed, implying loss from the energy source of the UNruh acceleration, which is the BH's gravitational field.

author: Michael Jones
sentences: Wikipedia says > Very close to the event horizon, spontaneous particle production always manifest as a pair of photons.

author: Michael Jones
sentences: It may happen that one of these photons passes beyond the event horizon, while the other escapes into the wider universe.

author: Michael Jones
sentences: A close analysis shows that the exponential redshifting effect of extreme gravity very close to the event horizon almost tears the escaping photon apart, and in addition very slightly amplifies it.

author: Michael Jones
sentences: The amplification gives rise to a "partner wave", which carries negative energy and passes through the event horizon, where it remains trapped, reducing the total energy of the black hole.

author: Michael Jones
sentences: The escaping photon adds an equal amount of positive energy to the wider universe outside the black hole.

author: Michael Jones
sentences: In this way, no matter or energy ever actually leaves the black hole itself.

author: Michael Jones
sentences: The matter becomes stickier when you consider entanglement entropy between the absorbed and lost particle.

sentences: ELI5: what is a computer doing when its "shutting down" why can't we just turn off the power and the machine stops working, and then works normally when we turn it on?

author: Jennifer Flores
sentences: Imaging if whenever the teacher says "okay, that's it for today", all the students stop mid writing, and just burst out of class all at once without listening to their assignements, or finishing their notes.

author: Jennifer Flores
sentences: That's similar to what happens to a computer when it's abruptly shut down, because the operating system is like a teacher, it's responsible for keeping all the apps and processes in check and provide them with their needs of memory and CPU power, that's why when shutdown a computer The operating system goes through the process of making sure every app and process have finished writing to memory and that there are no tasks to do before shutting down.

author: Rick Baker
sentences: I'll try answering this from a more chemistry pov.

author: Rick Baker
sentences: In medicines there are often parts of molecules (functional groups) that are known to commonly do similar things.

author: Rick Baker
sentences: For example, the functional group piperdine is often seen in neurotransmitters and drugs that effect the brain.

author: Rick Baker
sentences: Meanwhile if you look at hormones, like testosterone, they often have a 6,6,6,5 fused ring system.

author: Rick Baker
sentences: So as a chemist you can say "I want to make a drug that is good at combating depression" and then take a look at the common structures found in other molecules that have an effect on depression and start formulating an idea of what basic components your structure needs and how it can be improved upon.

author: Rick Baker
sentences: Maybe adding an extra functional group increases potency meaning dosage can be much lower, maybe there's a group on there that causes problems after it's been metabolized and your synthesis cuts it out.

author: Rick Baker
sentences: But very often the inspiration for medicines comes from chemicals already existent in nature however it takes a chemist to fine tune these natural products to be used in our own bodies.

author: Rick Baker
sentences: In reality though drugs are made through the combined efforts of organic chemists, biochemists, microbiologists, and medical doctors that all specialize in a different part of the process from reaction flask to pill bottle.

author: Kim Pierce
sentences: CMV: Religion has caused more overall harm than good If you count up all of the good vs bad things done in the name of religion, I think the bad outweighs the good.

author: Kim Pierce
sentences: Hypothetically if religion never formally developed and we as a species evolved our morality to support the same basic tenants that most modern religions follow today (eg.

author: Kim Pierce
sentences: no murder, stealing, harming, etc.

author: Kim Pierce
sentences: ), I believe that net-net we'd be better off than the harms that have been done in the name of religion (eg.

author: Kim Pierce
sentences: religious wars like the crusades, persecution of sexuality, systematic misogyny, distrust of science, etc.) .

author: Kim Pierce
sentences: I certainly acknowledge there have been benefits from religion like a focus on generosity, coordinating relief efforts, etc., but in my hypothetical, these would also have been done in communities whose sense of morality have developed.

author: Kim Pierce
sentences: For example, in countries that don't have a lot of religion, it's not like people without food aren't helped by non-religious organizations and people.

author: Kim Pierce
sentences: Or if a disaster hit, it's not only religious people that come to help.

author: Kim Pierce
sentences: To be clear, I know this is not a black and white issue, but what I'm saying is that if you add it all up, religion has not helped our society improve more than it could have if we just acted treated everyone with love and left our planet better than we found it.

author: Robert Stewart
sentences: We don't have a means of comparing religious and non religious societies primarily because almost all societies that formally developed had some religious component to them at least from what I have seen.

author: Robert Stewart
sentences: The second is religion prescribed a set of morals or behavior but what people do with those findings is based in the group behavior patterns.

author: Robert Stewart
sentences: Even if there was no religious set of ideals there would be another set of ideals people use to justify their positions, hiearchies, conquests for example see 21st century imperialism.

author: Robert Stewart
sentences: If part of your point relates to the idea that religion makes it so you don't question the belief system and also divides people up into different groups by virtue of being a different religion then that could be true but even post religious societies have that aspect such as nationalism.

author: Robert Stewart
sentences: My take is primarily based on sapiens by Andrew which describes human societal development as primarily consisting of stories which are able to connect large groups of people under various causes.

author: Robert Stewart
sentences: As science develops there is a semi religious element as well.

sentences: Science is different from religion in the sense that they have methods to test whether the maps presented in science accurately reflect reality via scientific method and scientific community.

sentences: However somethings that appear scientific are more or less stories that are collectively held true and justified as science.

sentences: Example capitalism is a specific model of production but the concept surrounding it like the american dream are another story perpetuated and bought into with no direct scientific validity though we treat it as such.

author: Thomas Smith
sentences: As to the userbox issue, I am finding there is a lot of confusion about what \"deletion from template space\" means.

author: Thomas Smith
sentences: It doesn't mean that userboxes will go away, just that they won't be in template space.

author: Thomas Smith
sentences: For example, look at my user page.

author: Thomas Smith
sentences: See the nice three userboxes?

author: Thomas Smith
sentences: I simply converted {{tl|User Irish}} to use {{tl|userbox}} layout, but my page still looks the same (and I can tweak to look exactly how I want with affecting anyone else).

author: Thomas Smith
sentences: So now if {{tl|User Irish}} gets deleted, my page is unchanged, I'm happy, and people wanting userboxes out of template space are happy.

author: Thomas Smith
sentences: Everyone's happy!

author: Thomas Smith
sentences: That's why I find it hard to understand why people object to moving userboxes out of template space.

author: Thomas Smith
sentences: They're not being \"deleted\", as the user pages will be still look the same, in fact there's a major advantage, as if I remained with {{tl|User Irish}} that would mean that if anyone vandalised that template, my page would change, along with 100's of others.

author: Thomas Smith
sentences: So, as far as I can see, there are many advantages to moving them to user space, with very few disadvantages (the only one being is that the source is a little longer in the user page, but how often do people edit their user page anyway?)

author: Thomas Smith
sentences: Hello again.

author: Thomas Smith
sentences: it was good to see your comment that you were going to switch to {{tl|userbox}} (and no, I don't think that classes as using template space).

author: Thomas Smith
sentences: If you have any problems, please let me know, and I can show how to do one or two, and the rest will be same (all the documentation is at {{tlt|userbox}}) Plus, by doing so, you'll learn how to cutomise them yourself, if you so choose.
